<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-angle-properties-of-a-circle" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Angle Properties of a Circle</title>
<introduction>
  <p>
    The circle is one of the most fundamental and symmetric shapes in geometry. 
    While we often focus on its area and circumference, the internal relationships 
    between its linear components—such as arcs, chords, and diameters—and the 
    angles they form are essential for advanced spatial reasoning.
  </p>
  <p>
    In this strand, we will investigate the consistent geometric rules that 
    govern how angles behave within a circle, covering center-angle 
    relationships, cyclic quadrilaterals, and real-world applications.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before we can understand these geometric properties, we must first learn the 
    vocabulary of a circle's anatomy. When straight lines intersect or boundaries 
    are divided, three fundamental elements emerge:
  </p>

  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Chords:</strong> A <em>chord</em> is a straight line segment whose 
          endpoints both lie on the circumference of the circle. Think of it as a straight 
          bridge crossing from one side of the circle to the other. The longest 
          possible chord in any circle is the one that passes directly through the 
          centre—this special chord is known as the <strong>diameter</strong>.
          <figure xml:id="figure-circle-chord">
    <caption>A circle with centre O showing a chord BA</caption>
    <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Define the Centre ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
            
            % --- Define two points on the circumference to create a chord ---
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 30 radius 2.5]\tkzGetPoint{A}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 150 radius 2.5]\tkzGetPoint{B}

            % --- Draw the Circle ---
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,A)

            % --- Draw the Chord (in blue for emphasis) ---
            \tkzDrawSegment[thick, color=blue](A,B)

            % --- Label the chord line text midway ---
            \path (A) -- (B) node[midway, below=2pt, color=blue] {Chord};

            % --- Draw Points and Labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints[size=4,fill=black](O,A,B)
            \tkzLabelPoint[below](O){$O$}
            \tkzLabelPoint[right](A){$A$}
            \tkzLabelPoint[left](B){$B$}
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Arcs:</strong> An <em>arc</em> is a continuous portion of the circle's 
          circumference (the curved boundary). When we place two points on a circle, 
          they divide the boundary into two paths. The shorter path is called the 
          <strong>minor arc</strong>, while the longer path around the other side is 
          called the <strong>major arc</strong>. If the two points lie exactly on 
          opposite ends of a diameter, the resulting arc is a <strong>semicircle</strong>.
          <figure xml:id="figure-circle-arc">
    <caption>A circle with centre O showing a highlighted arc BA</caption>
    <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Define the Centre ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
            
            % --- Define the endpoints of the arc on the circumference ---
            % Radius is 2.5 cm. Arc runs counter-clockwise from 30 to 120 degrees.
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 30 radius 2.5]\tkzGetPoint{A}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 120 radius 2.5]\tkzGetPoint{B}

            % --- Draw the background Circle ---
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,A)

            % --- Highlight the Arc BA in a bold color ---
            \tkzDrawArc[ultra thick, color=red](O,A)(B)

            % --- Place a label text dynamically near the center of the arc ---
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 75 radius 2.8]\tkzGetPoint{ArcLabel}
            \node[color=red] at (ArcLabel) {Arc $AB$};

            % --- Draw Points and Labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints[size=4,fill=black](O,A,B)
            \tkzLabelPoint[below](O){$O$}
            \tkzLabelPoint[right](A){$A$}
            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](B){$B$}
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Segments:</strong> A <em>segment</em> is the two-dimensional region 
          trapped between a chord and its corresponding arc. Unlike a slice of pizza 
          (which is called a <em>sector</em> because its boundaries meet at the centre), 
          a segment is created by a single straight cut across the circle. Just like 
          arcs, segments are classified as <strong>minor segments</strong> (the smaller area) 
          or <strong>major segments</strong> (the larger area).
          <figure xml:id="figure-circle-segment">
    <caption>A circle with centre O showing a highlighted minor segment</caption>
    <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Define the Centre ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
            
            % --- Define endpoints on the circumference ---
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 30 radius 2.5]\tkzGetPoint{A}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 150 radius 2.5]\tkzGetPoint{B}

            % --- Fill the Segment region ---
            % This fills the area from point A along the arc to B, then closes back to A via the chord
            \fill[fill=red!25] (A) arc[start angle=30, end angle=150, radius=2.5] -- cycle;

            % --- Draw the background Circle ---
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,A)

            % --- Draw the Chord boundary ---
            \tkzDrawSegment[thick, color=blue!80!black](A,B)

            % --- Draw the Arc boundary ---
            \tkzDrawArc[thick, color=blue!80!black](O,A)(B)

            % --- Label the Segment region ---
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 90 radius 1.7]\tkzGetPoint{SegLabel}
            \node[color=red!80!black, font=\small] at (SegLabel) {Segment};

            % --- Draw Points and Labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints[size=4,fill=black](O,A,B)
            \tkzLabelPoint[below](O){$O$}
            \tkzLabelPoint[right](A){$A$}
            \tkzLabelPoint[left](B){$B$}
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>
    Understanding how these three parts interact is the key to solving circle geometry. 
    For instance, how does the length of a chord affect the size of the arc it cuts off? 
    What kind of angles are created when we draw lines from the endpoints of a chord to 
    the centre versus the circumference? We will explore these exact questions in the 
    sections that follow.
  </p>
 </introduction>
